# Architecture — {{.Project}}

> This document is the standard a reviewer evaluates code against. If it
> isn't here, it isn't a requirement.

## Principles

1. **Package boundaries are explicit.** Each package has one job. Public
   API at the package root; implementation details in `internal/` or
   unexported types.

2. **Errors are values.** Return `error`, don't `panic`. Wrap with
   `fmt.Errorf("doing X: %w", err)` so callers can `errors.Is` /
   `errors.As`.

3. **No `init()` for business logic.** Use explicit constructors. `init()`
   is for registration only (e.g. database/sql drivers).

4. **Dependencies flow inward.** The `cmd/` layer wires; `internal/`
   contains domain logic; nothing in `internal/` imports `cmd/`.

5. **Concurrency is opt-in.** Functions are sequential by default. Any
   goroutine has a documented owner and a clear lifetime — no fire-and-
   forget background work.

6. **Tests are real.** Use `t.TempDir()` for filesystem fixtures.
   In-memory SQLite for store tests. `httptest.Server` for HTTP. Mock
   only at process boundaries (network, time, randomness).

## Module map

> Fill in once you carve out the first real features. Until then this
> section is the catch-all for "what lives where".

| Package          | Responsibility |
|------------------|----------------|
| `cmd/<bin>/`     | Process entry point (flags, wiring, exit codes) |
| `internal/<pkg>` | Domain logic; pure Go, no `cmd/` imports |
| `_test.go`       | Tests live next to the code they exercise |
